			<p>University of Central Florida Economics Professor Glenn W. Harrison has been named the inaugural Richard T. Crotty Orange County Endowed Chair in the College of Business Administration. Harrison, a native of Australia, joined UCF in 2003. In his new role, he will teach and conduct research in areas relating to urban and regional economic research. Additionally, he will serve as a critical resource for the Institute for Economic Competitiveness, which is located within the college. <br />
<br />
&quot;I am honored to be the holder of the inaugural Richard T. Crotty Orange County Endowed Chair in Economics,&quot; Harrison said. &quot;Mayor Crotty has been a longtime supporter of the evolution of UCF as a research institution, and the use of research to guide public policy. It is appropriate that the name of the chair reflect his long-standing devotion to the role of scholarship in society.&quot;<br />
<br />
Harrison&rsquo;s research interests include experimental economics, environmental and resource economics and international trade policy. He is widely published in those areas and has made numerous presentations throughout the world.&nbsp; He received his Ph.D. in Economics from UCLA.<br />
<br />
&ldquo;Glenn Harrison is the type of faculty member that you want to stay at UCF,&quot; said Thomas L. Keon, dean of the UCF College of Business Administration. &quot;His classes are interesting and enlightening to students and his research is known worldwide because of the quality of his work. To be able to provide him with this prestigious chair will help the university reach national prominence.&quot;</p>
<hr />
<p><br />
<b>UCF Stands For Opportunity: </b>The University of Central Florida is a metropolitan research university that ranks as the 6th largest in the nation with more than 50,000 students. UCF's first classes were offered in 1968. The university offers impressive academic and research environments that power the region's economic development. UCF's culture of opportunity is driven by our diversity, Orlando environment, history of entrepreneurship and our youth, relevance and energy. For more information, visit http://news.ucf.edu<br />
&nbsp;</p>
		
	
